8 Annotation Levels
*******************

Simply Annotate provides a three-tier annotation level system for
progressive code exploration.  Each annotation is tagged with a level
when created, and you can cycle through levels to focus on annotations
at a particular granularity.

8.1 Level Overview
==================

‘file’
     Whole-file descriptions.  Use this level for high-level summaries
     of what a file does, its purpose in the project, or overall
     architecture notes.
‘defun’
     Function or element descriptions.  The default level, suitable for
     documenting individual functions, classes, or major code blocks.
‘line’
     Individual syntactical elements.  Use this level for fine-grained
     notes about specific expressions, variables, or implementation
     details.

8.2 How Levels Work
===================

Only annotations matching the active level are styled.  Annotations at
other levels have their visual markers (highlights, fringe indicators,
inline blocks) removed, but the underlying text remains visible:

   • *Display*: Only overlays matching the active level show highlights,
     fringe indicators, and inline blocks.
   • *Navigation*: ‘M-n’ and ‘M-p’ visit only annotations at the active
     level.
   • *Editing*: ‘M-s j’ on annotated text only opens annotations
     matching the active level.
   • *Header display*: The annotation count and position indicator
     reflect only the active level.

8.3 Cycling Levels
==================

Use ‘M-s ]’ to cycle forward and ‘M-s [’ to cycle backward through
levels:

     M-s ]: file ⇒ defun ⇒ line ⇒ file ⇒ ...
     M-s [: line ⇒ defun ⇒ file ⇒ line ⇒ ...

   The header-line shows annotation counts for every level, with the
active level in bold (e.g. ‘FILE:2 | DEFUN:5 | LINE:3’).

8.4 Direct Level Selection
==========================

Use ‘M-x simply-annotate-set-level’ to jump directly to a specific level
via ‘completing-read’.

8.5 Creating Annotations at a Level
===================================

New annotations inherit the currently active level.  For example, if you
cycle to ‘file’ level and then create an annotation, it will be tagged
as a file-level annotation.

8.6 Backward Compatibility
==========================

Existing annotations created before the levels feature was introduced
automatically default to the ‘defun’ level.  No database migration is
required.

8.7 Use Cases
=============

8.7.1 Code Exploration
----------------------

  1. Start at ‘file’ level to read high-level descriptions of what each
     file does
  2. Switch to ‘defun’ level to understand individual functions
  3. Drill down to ‘line’ level for implementation details

8.7.2 LLM-Generated Documentation
---------------------------------

Annotation levels provide a natural structure for AI-generated code
descriptions:

   • Generate ‘file’-level summaries for project overview
   • Generate ‘defun’-level documentation for API reference
   • Generate ‘line’-level annotations for detailed code walkthroughs

   Users can then browse these layered annotations at their preferred
depth.


